## PARA layout

- **triage/** - landing zone for anything that doesn't obviously fit elsewhere; sorted at the next review.
- **projects/** - {{what a "project" means here. Default: time-bound work with a committed deliverable, one folder per project, each holding a `brief.md` and, where relevant, a `sources/` subfolder. This flavor has no per-project `actions.md` - capture next steps as prose in the brief.}}
- **areas/** - ongoing responsibilities. `business/` = running narrative. `network/` = one file per person.{{ Add any other area subfolders this vault needs.}}
- **resources/** - reusable reference. `prompts/` = reusable specs and drafts. `ideas/` = concept-stage ventures with no committed outcome; same `brief.md` shape as a project for easy promotion. `mds/` = collected `.md` sources (see the flip workflow below); never browsed manually.
- **archive/** - inactive artifacts. `meetings/` = dated meeting/chat/email records.{{ Add `projects/` = completed work and `ideas/` = shelved concepts, if this vault archives finished projects and retired ideas (both filled by `/para-archive`).}}

Promote `resources/ideas/<x>` to `projects/` (or to the vault's active bucket) once there is a committed outcome. Ideas with no traction at 6+ months retire to `archive/ideas/` (via `/para-archive`).

Root `README.md` is the master document, single source of truth for identity, operating model, and track record. It sits above the PARA folders so the reader never sees it; derived outputs regenerate from it.

### Archive hygiene

What a clean `archive/` looks like (applied on the way in, and audited by `/para-deep-clean`):

- **No live work in the archive.** An archived entity has zero open next-steps - every item done, or open items softened to an explicit "fully closed; minor gaps not material" note in the brief. Surviving work is routed out *before* archiving. (This flavor tracks next steps as prose, not `[ ]` tasks, so "no live work" means no open prose next-steps left dangling.)
- **History archives; living references go to `resources/`.** Brief and one-time migration/handoff notes are history - they archive with the entity. Reusable material (playbooks, positioning/strategy docs, anything other live work links to as a resource) is routed to `resources/<name>/`, not buried in the archive.
- **No loose files at the archive root.** Everything under `archive/` lives in a subfolder (`meetings/`, `projects/`, ...). A stray top-level file is misfiled.
- **Minimum record.** Each archived entity carries a status marker (why it's archived) and a `brief.md`/`README.md`, so it's self-explanatory years later.
- **Zero dangling links.** Moving something into the archive repoints every inbound reference (contacts, areas, README, other entities) in the same pass; a stale link is rot. A historical mention *inside* the archived folder itself is fine.

## Filing rules

- **Contacts**: one file per person at `areas/network/<firstname-lastname>.md` (kebab-case, no diacritics). Relationship context as prose. {{If the maintainer has their own naming for some folders/people, preserve it verbatim; their style takes precedence over the convention.}}
- **Next steps**: this flavor has **no `actions.md` files**. Capture next steps as prose inside the relevant brief, area file, or contact file. Never create an `actions.md`.
- **Dated meeting/chat/email artifacts**: `archive/meetings/YYYYMMDD Description.ext`.
- **Source documents**: {{the naming convention for filed documents, e.g. `YYYYMMDD <Who> <Description>.<ext>`. The /para-triage skill applies this convention literally; if you leave it undefined, /para-triage will ask before renaming anything.}}
- **Shared workstreams across contacts**: narrate in the primary contact's file; the other files get a pointer line.
- **Project brief + relationship**: the contact file is the relationship summary; the project folder holds the brief and execution detail. Cross-link both ways.

## Language

Folders and structural files in English. Content (notes, contacts, briefs) may be in any language, matching the source. Don't translate unless asked.

## iPad access and rendering ({{Reader}})

{{Reader}} works from an iPad and consumes this vault read-only as PDFs through Google Drive. Two iPadOS + Google Drive quirks shape the vault:

1. Drive's iOS Files-provider only reliably opens types iOS has a native preview handler for (`.pdf`, images, video, Office docs). `.md` and large `.txt` tap-to-open is unreliable.
2. Drive doesn't hide dotfiles. The only way to keep `CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/`, `.obsidian/`, `.git/` out of the reader's view is to make sure their access points don't include the vault root.

### Access model

The reader's personal My Drive has a folder named after this vault with Google Drive shortcuts pointing to `triage/`, `projects/`, `areas/`, `resources/`, `archive/`. They navigate via iOS Files into those shortcuts and never reach the vault root. If a new top-level folder is added, flag that a matching shortcut needs to be created.

### `.md` <-> `.pdf` workflow (collect / spread / render)

Two states, flipped with [`flip.ps1`](flip.ps1):

- **Collected** (default, what the reader sees): every `.md` lives in `resources/mds/` with its vault path encoded in the filename (separator `__`, e.g. `projects__<entity>__brief.md`). PARA folders contain only `.pdf` files.
- **Spread** (editing): `.md` files sit next to their `.pdf` siblings under PARA. This is the state [`render.ps1`](render.ps1) operates on.

Edit cycle:

```
.\flip.ps1 spread    # .md back to PARA paths
# edit in your editor
.\render.ps1         # regenerate .pdf siblings
.\flip.ps1 collect   # .md back to resources/mds/
```

- Both flip modes are idempotent; `-DryRun` previews. `render.ps1` re-renders only when `.md` is newer than `.pdf` (`-Force` to override) and denylists `mds/`.
- Ignored everywhere: `CLAUDE.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `.claude/`, `.git/`, `.obsidian/`, `.vscode/`. Vault-root `README.md` is left in place (sits above PARA; the reader never sees it).
- Engine: Puppeteer + `github-markdown-css` via [`render.mjs`](render.mjs). Install: `npm install -g puppeteer marked github-markdown-css`.
- Identical copies of `render.ps1`, `render.mjs`, `flip.ps1` live in each vault of this flavor. Canonical master: the para-os repo, under `flavors/readonly-ipad/pipeline/`. Change the master first (or fold a vault-side fix back into it), then propagate to every vault.

### File types via Drive provider

| Type | Behavior | Action |
|---|---|---|
| `.pdf`, images, video | iOS Quick Look | Works as-is |
| `.xlsx` / `.docx` / `.pptx` | Microsoft app (read-only without M365); edits via Sheets/Docs | Works as-is |
| `.md` / `.txt` | Unreliable | Render to `.pdf`; don't use `.txt` for read content |

### File formats: real files only

The substrate is real, readable files. Google-native Docs/Sheets/Slides sync as `.gdoc`/`.gsheet` stubs that `flip.ps1`, `render.mjs`, and `mv` can't relocate and the Read tool can't read. When cleaning a drive, convert them to `.docx`/`.xlsx` (or Markdown/CSV for our own content) so the pipeline can move, render, and track them. New files the reader saves should be Word/Excel, not Google Docs/Sheets, for the same reason.

### Notes for Claude sessions

- If the vault is already spread, the maintainer may be mid-edit; don't re-collect without checking.
- If the reader reports a `.md` not opening, the answer is "look for the PDF sibling", not a technical fix on their side.

## Memory

This vault on disk IS the memory. Do not use the agent's built-in memory feature, and do not create a `memory/` folder or session-log files. The agent reads the vault fresh each session; the git history is the audit log. Durable facts belong in the file they describe: conventions in this `CLAUDE.md`, identity and operating model in `README.md`, and everything else in the relevant project, idea, or contact note.

## Do not add

- **Action tracking** - this flavor's reader doesn't use action lists. Capture next steps as prose in the relevant brief, area, or contact file; no `actions.md` files.
- **Templates** - do not create per-contact or per-project templates preemptively. Wait until a second instance proves the shape, then document it here.
- **Derived outputs as standalone files** - web copy, deck content, one-pager text regenerate from `README.md`. Do not let them drift into separate source-of-truth files.
- **Content rewrites during reorganization** - structure changes preserve copy verbatim. Fix wording in a later, dedicated pass.
- {{Anything else that belongs in a different vault or system, e.g. "Accounting, invoicing, financial records - belong in a separate vault (one vault per life context)."}}

